d National HDRs in Policies and Programmes\u201d (Colombo, Sri Lanka, 24-26 September 2003), the training work- shop was conceived as a platform for cross-coun- try sharing and collective exploration of critical concepts and issues of human development. The challenges faced by different stakeholders in human development analysis, process and reporting had been kept in mind while designing this training. In fact, preparatory work was conducted to ascertain the needs of all participants and the areas of strength of each team. Participants had an opportunity to strengthen their perspectives on the human development approach, share experiences and learn from regional best practices, understand the importance and role of national and regional HDRs and collectively evolve strategies for translating messages of regional and national HDRs into programmes and policies. The- matic break-out group discussions (on trade, hu- man security and governance) and exercises were introduced to facilitate the application of concepts and tools considered. By combining concepts and practical tools, the workshop sought to clarify the distinctions between: \ufffd The HD concept and its differences with other development paradigms \ufffd Human Development Reports at the global, re- gional and national levels \ufffd Human Development Index and other indices measuring HD \ufffd The relationship between reporting on HD and monitoring progress on Millennium Development Goals (MDGs). 1.3 1.3 1.3 1.3 1.3PPPPParticipants articipants articipants articipants articipants The workshop brought together 30 representatives from 12 countries of UNDP Country Offices, NHDR Team members/coordinators, government officials and statisticians from Cambodia, China, East Timor, Fiji, Indonesia, Iran, Laos, Malaysia, Mongolia, Pakistan, Papua New Guinea and Thai- land. Resource people included members of the HDRO, RBAP, APRI, independent consultants, and the NHDR Focal Point from Bosnia Herzegovina for cross-regional exchanges. Partici- pants represented the global, regional and national experiences with the preparation of Human De- velopment Reports. 1.4 1.4 1.4 1.4 1.4Evaluation of the T Evaluation of the T Evaluation of the T Evaluation of the T Evaluation of the Training raining raining raining raining W W W W Workshop orkshop orkshop orkshop orkshop To improve the structure and contents of future APRI regional training workshops, participants were requested to compile a workshop evaluation form at the end of the training.", "start_char_idx": null, "end_char_idx": null, "text_template": "{metadata_str}\n\n{content}", "metadata_template": "{key}: {value}", "metadata_seperator": "\n"}, "__type__": "1"}, "9dfeed04-294c-4b34-8e01-8fa4025f7b1e": {"__data__": {"id_": "9dfeed04-294c-4b34-8e01-8fa4025f7b1e", "embedding": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/potential-and-challenges-human-development-analysis-process-and-reporting", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "excluded_embed_metadata_keys": [], "excluded_llm_metadata_keys": [], "relationships": {"1": {"node_id": "Potential and Challenges in Human Development: Analysis, Process and Reporting", "node_type": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/potential-and-challenges-human-development-analysis-process-and-reporting", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "hash": "fb83a6d0acfa625e36e5bcf7d625c9d7067c276da2ef89d50dbe37fe986c8741"}, "2": {"node_id": "cbccc39c-ebd4-4cab-a8ca-38746df13543", "node_type": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/potential-and-challenges-human-development-analysis-process-and-reporting", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "