 decent standard of living\u201d (UNDP 1990). SECTION II he HD Concept and its Application in the Asia-Pacific Region Figur Figur Figur Figur Figure 2.1 Mutually R e 2.1 Mutually R e 2.1 Mutually R e 2.1 Mutually R e 2.1 Mutually Reinfor einfor einfor einfor einforcing Capabilities cing Capabilities cing Capabilities cing Capabilities cing Capabilities Source: Human Development Report, 2002 Fundamental to enlarging these choices is the proc- ess of building human capabilities \u2013 having a healthy life, having access to resources needed for a decent standard of living and having the ability to partici- pate in the life of the community. Political freedom and participation are part of human development, both as development goals in their own right and as means for advancing human development. In fact, political freedom empowers people to claim their economic and social rights, while education increases their ability to demand economic and social policies that respond to their priorities (Figure 2.1). 5 The HD Concept and its Application in the Asia-Pacific Region The HD Concept and its Application in the Asia-Pacific Region By according due priority to economic growth along- side issues of equity, sustainability and participation, the human development paradigm presents a com- prehensive and integrated perspective of development. The differences between the human development approach and, broadly speaking, non-human devel- opment approach are presented in Table 2.1. Despite its considerable popularity, the human de- velopment concept is often misunderstood and con- TTTTTable 2.1 able 2.1 able 2.1 able 2.1 able 2.1 Differ Differ Differ Differ Differences Between HD and Non-HD Appr ences Between HD and Non-HD Appr ences Between HD and Non-HD Appr ences Between HD and Non-HD Appr ences Between HD and Non-HD Approach oach oach oach oach HD Approach Well-being, dignity, freedom; ad- dressing inequalities, exclusion and poverty For people People No recipes, but elements 